00:50:50.210 --> 00:50:51.460
Are you stiff in your journal?

00:50:51.460 --> 00:50:51.960
No.

00:50:51.960 --> 00:50:54.460
But more so just like capturing.

00:50:54.460 --> 00:50:56.590
I guess similar to what
you all talked about

00:50:56.590 --> 00:50:58.180
and capturing the
city of Atlanta.

00:50:58.180 --> 00:50:59.890
Like how do I capture stories?

00:50:59.890 --> 00:51:03.320
I'm into sociology so I do a
lot of type of ethnographies.

00:51:03.320 --> 00:51:05.350
So I want to know
how do I really tell

00:51:05.350 --> 00:51:09.910
the stories of other people in
I guess like a free way that

00:51:09.910 --> 00:51:14.110
is not just jaded or bias?

00:51:14.110 --> 00:51:15.880
You're going to be
bias, and that's OK.

00:51:15.880 --> 00:51:17.860
Your bias is your point of view.

00:51:17.860 --> 00:51:20.292
And that's a good thing.

00:51:20.292 --> 00:51:22.000
So I think that's one
thing, is don't try

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:23.837
to run from your point of view.

00:51:23.837 --> 00:51:24.670
What is it they say?

00:51:24.670 --> 00:51:26.340
It's not a bug, it's a feature?

00:51:26.340 --> 00:51:27.380
Yeah.

00:51:27.380 --> 00:51:28.510
That's what that is.

00:51:28.510 --> 00:51:30.100
But just don't worry.

00:51:30.100 --> 00:51:31.660
It sounds like you're worrying
about what someone else is

00:51:31.660 --> 00:51:32.577
going to say about it.

00:51:32.577 --> 00:51:35.040
You're critiquing it
as you're writing it.

00:51:35.040 --> 00:51:37.200
Writing and publishing
are two different things.

00:51:37.200 --> 00:51:38.610
Writing is where
you can be free.

00:51:38.610 --> 00:51:41.180
It's just between you and
the page, and later on worry

00:51:41.180 --> 00:51:42.930
about what someone
else is going to think.

00:51:42.930 --> 00:51:44.400
Worry about an audience later.

00:51:44.400 --> 00:51:46.440
But just write for
your own pleasure.

00:51:46.440 --> 00:51:49.710
Write a story that
speaks to your heart,

00:51:49.710 --> 00:51:51.490
and once you do that
it will be free.

00:51:51.490 --> 00:51:52.980
It will not be
stiff and you just

00:51:52.980 --> 00:51:54.960
worry about all that
other stuff later.

00:51:54.960 --> 00:51:55.740
Thank you.

00:51:55.740 --> 00:51:57.180
And eavesdrop on people.

00:51:57.180 --> 00:51:58.050
Listen to people.

00:51:58.050 --> 00:51:59.383
You want to write about Atlanta?

00:51:59.383 --> 00:52:03.000
Go someplace in a public place
and sit and listen to people.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:04.980
I mean that's a
great story you have

00:52:04.980 --> 00:52:06.360
about in American Marriage.

00:52:06.360 --> 00:52:08.790
But just listen to people
because not only will you

00:52:08.790 --> 00:52:12.270
get great stories,
but you also will

00:52:12.270 --> 00:52:16.590
be able to be more familiar with
the rhythms of how people talk.

00:52:16.590 --> 00:52:18.150
Listen to a conversation
and then see

00:52:18.150 --> 00:52:19.590
if you can reproduce it.

00:52:19.590 --> 00:52:21.180
Listen to what people
are saying when

00:52:21.180 --> 00:52:23.730
they're arguing
in a public place,

00:52:23.730 --> 00:52:25.105
trying to keep
their voices down.

00:52:25.105 --> 00:52:27.438
What did they say when they're
arguing in a public place

00:52:27.438 --> 00:52:29.580
and don't care about
keeping their voices down?

00:52:29.580 --> 00:52:31.200
But just listen to people.

00:52:31.200 --> 00:52:33.720
Listen to what they say
and try to figure out

00:52:33.720 --> 00:52:36.518
how much you can glean
from what they actually say

00:52:36.518 --> 00:52:38.310
and then from the things
they're not saying

00:52:38.310 --> 00:52:39.240
and put it in your journal.

00:52:39.240 --> 00:52:39.823
Write it down.

00:52:39.823 --> 00:52:42.420
Thank you.

00:52:42.420 --> 00:52:43.040
