warmth in the room

00:52:50.990 --> 00:52:53.810
by the personal
relationship I feel

00:52:53.810 --> 00:52:57.620
I have with you having
never met either one of you.

00:52:57.620 --> 00:53:00.140
And I'm really curious
because I really

00:53:00.140 --> 00:53:02.210
feel that there's something
about the mentorship

00:53:02.210 --> 00:53:05.930
and the sisterhood and the
auntie and the mother/daughter

00:53:05.930 --> 00:53:08.630
that is going on on
this stage that we

00:53:08.630 --> 00:53:11.490
need to have in this country.

00:53:11.490 --> 00:53:13.010
I'm a physician here in Atlanta.

00:53:13.010 --> 00:53:15.930
I'm 55 years old, so on
the end of my career.

00:53:15.930 --> 00:53:19.520
And so there were no
black female physicians,

00:53:19.520 --> 00:53:22.040
and I was here in Atlanta at
Georgia Baptist or Atlanta

00:53:22.040 --> 00:53:23.840
Medical Center
during my residency.

00:53:23.840 --> 00:53:26.090
So I'm trying to
figure out, how is it

00:53:26.090 --> 00:53:28.520
that we're in the
same generation

00:53:28.520 --> 00:53:33.402
and that mentorship was not
there for me as a physician?

00:53:33.402 --> 00:53:35.360
And I want to be able to
give it going forward.

00:53:35.360 --> 00:53:36.830
So how is it that, what?

00:53:36.830 --> 00:53:38.430
20 years ago?

00:53:38.430 --> 00:53:38.930
30.

00:53:38.930 --> 00:53:41.450
30 years ago that
you all had this

00:53:41.450 --> 00:53:45.290
and have this warm powerful
humility that I just

00:53:45.290 --> 00:53:47.000
feel like we want to
have as black women.

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:48.375
And I feel like
sometimes there's

00:53:48.375 --> 00:53:52.280
this something that says,
yeah, it's mutually exclusive.

00:53:52.280 --> 00:53:54.470
I can't have it and
you have it too.

00:53:54.470 --> 00:53:55.970
And how can we do
that for ourselves

00:53:55.970 --> 00:53:59.120
as black women and also to do
it for ourselves as Americans

00:53:59.120 --> 00:54:00.020
and human beings?

00:54:00.020 --> 00:54:02.120
Because that's the
end to all this stuff

00:54:02.120 --> 00:54:04.040
you're talking about
that's going on today?

00:54:04.040 --> 00:54:05.320
So I want to acknowledge that.

00:54:09.830 --> 00:54:12.600
When I teach, I tell my
students when they find out

00:54:12.600 --> 00:54:14.975
about opportunities, they'll
try to hoard an opportunity.

00:54:14.975 --> 00:54:16.970
They'll find out
there's a fellowship

00:54:16.970 --> 00:54:20.600
and they won't tell the
others because that'll lessen

00:54:20.600 --> 00:54:22.170
their own chance of getting it.

00:54:22.170 --> 00:54:25.280
And I have to tell
them that's OK.

00:54:25.280 --> 00:54:28.640
You have to let the
others try, even if it

00:54:28.640 --> 00:54:32.750
means that it could cost you.

00:54:32.750 --> 00:54:34.640
I mean the students,
they know that the more

00:54:34.640 --> 00:54:37.340
people who apply the lesser
your own chances of getting it.

00:54:37.340 --> 00:54:38.450
That's just the truth.

00:54:38.450 --> 00:54:40.130
So the reason you
share with others

00:54:40.130 --> 00:54:42.047
is not that we can both
have it, because there

00:54:42.047 --> 00:54:44.005
are going to be some
things we can't both have,

00:54:44.005 --> 00:54:45.060
but that's not the point.

00:54:45.060 --> 00:54:47.747
The point is that we can
all have the opportunity,

00:54:47.747 --> 00:54:49.580
and that's what I think
is a thing to learn.

00:54:49.580 --> 00:54:52.918
People are so afraid
of losing something,

00:54:52.918 --> 00:54:55.460
but I don't think the answer is
to tell them they won't lose.

00:54:55.460 --> 00:54:58.280
The answer is that
you might lose that,

00:54:58.280 --> 00:55:00.560
but what you gain
from helping someone

00:55:00.560 --> 00:55:03.260
is more valuable than
that thing you might lose.

00:55:03.260 --> 00:55:05.100
Perfect.

00:55:05.100 --> 00:55:07.100
I also think the
